One of the first concerted efforts by Northerners to oppose the Union’s war effort during the American Civil War took place on the western edge of Schuylkill County in Pennsylvania’s turbulent Coal Region. These small-scale riots lasting less than a week proved to be a harbinger of much bloodier, more violent uprisings against the draft in 1863.

In late October 1862, Irish mineworkers from the county’s mining districts took up arms
